  Part 1: Why we should care about Russian hacking in the Rust Belt
 Supposedley the Russians hacked into some voting booths and may have influcenced the 2016 presidential election. In fact Reality Winner, the woman from the NSA who supposedley leaked this information to the Intercept back in SITE, just pleaded guilty and was sentenced to 5 years in prison*.

I know what you're thinking: "OMG if I have to hear the word 'Russian' one more time I am going to drop-kick my computer." But this is not speculative smear journalism nor is it political...it's real and could happen right here in the Rust Belt! It's true. Pay attention, and I promise I will not use the "R" word one more time in this entire post. Control-F that shit if you don't believe me!

Apparently it's really easy to hack into voting booths: SITE. Probably even more alarming is that it's really easy to hack into satellites as well (SITE). You think you're getting directions to go to TGIF...but really you end up at Red Lobster. Oh those sneaky satellite hackers!

I know basically nothing about satellites so let's stick with voting. The Rust Belt is one of the most highly contested regions (SITE) in presidential elections. Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Michigan are huge swing states and the red vs blue line is as thin as ever, which means the Rust Belt could be a target for vote-hackers in the future. Let's be honest, nobody's gonna try to hack a booth in Alabama and convince everyone that they're now full of liberals.

So let's break down this voting-booth hacking story and give a clearer picture of what they describe. Then we'll talk about how we can use technology to have more secure voting systems. Finally I'll even use my soapbox to talk about how flawed our voting system is (with or without voting booths and software). It's time to take the power back!

* this is slightly off topic, but here is a really interesting post (which is a little dated) talking about Reality Winner and the irony of her whistleblowing. 

