  --------------------------------------------------

Part 4/Bonus: A better system of voting
In both the last election and the 2000 election between Buch and Gore, the Democrat candidate won the popular vote, yet the Republican won the Electoral College, granting them the presidency. Not surprisingly, this caused many voters to complain and say we should move to having a popular vote. Surprising to some, this is a very bad idea, and in fact the electoral college is vastly superior to this. Unfortunately the electoral college still isn't that great either.

  There are a few reasons why a straight popular vote is ill-advised. If we give the candidate with just the highest percentage of votes. then in a proper two-party system someone would have to get 51% of the votes to win. But we have more than two parties...in the last election there were Green and Libertarian candidates. Suppose Gary Johnson were to get more votes...you coucld end up in a situation where a candidate wins with only 34% of the country voting for them...ie. 66% of the country DID NOT vote for them.
  
  Another issue comes down to how populations are distributed. While we have a big country, the majority of the population lives in a handful of city centers: LA, NY, Houston, etc. Moving to a popular vote would effectively mean that a candidate could campaign in about 10 cities across the US, the only one in the Rust Belt being Chicago. Ouch.

  If you think this is unlikely, just suppose a candidate ran on a platform of "everyone within city 15 miles of a city center whose population is greater than 3 million people will get free wi-fi, but everyone outside of that will get a tax increase to pay for the city-dwellers wifi." We've had candidates who ran on crazier ideas than that. In fact, an idea like this would almost guarantee somebody victory...even though roughly 50% of the population would get screwed. SITE: here are some other sources which break down these points better.

So the electoral college, while flawed, at least ensures that candidates have to campaign in smaller regions and address those voters' issues to secure a victory. SITE: Hilary Clinton did not campaign once in the state of Wisconsin, lost the perennially blue state, and ultimately the election. One of the most hotly contested regions in the last 3 elections were surrounding Youngstown, Ohio...who ever talks about Youngstown unless it's a conversation about "regions outputting the best college football coaches" or "cities in the country which may be worse than Flint, MI?"

A better system to either is preferential voting. You get a list of candidates A through E, and then have to rank them from 1 to 5. Each number is assigned a point, and the candidate with the most points wins. So all those people who say "well I would prefer THIS candidate...but they're not gonna win so I guess I'll instead vote for THAT candidate" wouldn't have to do that. Not surprisingly, doing this would get more third-party candidates elected...also not surprisingly neither the Republicans nor Democrats (SITE) want this kind of system.

So do yourself a favor and call up your representative/governor/senator/council-person and say "Hey, can we start voting online cause having to deal with those old ladies at the voting booths sucks, plus it's way more secure than how we currently do things. Oh and my niece is a software engineer with a minor in policy so you should hire her to build a secure voting site for you. Also you would never have won if we did preferential voting. K thanks bye."
